  "prompt": "What are the different types of absorbable surgical sutures?",
  "response": "There are several types of absorbable surgical sutures, classified based on their material composition and characteristics:\n\n1. Natural Absorbable Sutures:\n- Catgut (plain and chromic)\n- Derived from collagen\n- Quick absorption (7-10 days)\n- Less commonly used now\n\n2. Synthetic Absorbable Sutures:\na) Polyglactin 910 (Vicryl)\n- Braided polyglycolic acid\n- Moderate tensile strength\n- Absorption in 60-90 days\n\nb) Polydioxanone (PDS)\n- Monofilament synthetic suture\n- Long-lasting strength\n- Absorption in 180-210 days\n\nc) Polyglecaprone (Monocryl)\n- Monofilament synthetic suture\n- Low tissue reactivity\n- Absorption in 90-120 days\n\nd) Polytrimethylene carbonate (Maxon)\n- Monofilament synthetic suture\n- High initial strength\n- Absorption in 180-210 days\n\n3. Glycomer-based Sutures\n- Rapid absorption\n- Low tissue reaction\n- Used in delicate tissue repairs\n\nEach type has specific characteristics suited to different surgical requirements and tissue types.",
